Angular Elements show a lot of promise to enterprises running multiple projects so we can keep things DRY. However, getting Angular Elements consumed in another app is still quite a chore. I'd love to see this process simplified. 

Currently I'm able to overcome the zone duplication issue in Angular consumers by piggy backing off the zone in the consuming Angular application (Reference: https://angular-extensions.github.io/elements/#/docs/change-detection) by removing zone.js from polyfills in the angular elements application and bootstrapping like such:
`  
platformBrowserDynamic()
    .bootstrapModule(AppModule, { ngZone: (window as any).ngZone })
    .catch((err) => console.log(err));
`
Then I set up the consuming app module like such:
`
export class AppModule {
  constructor(private ngZone: NgZone) {
    (window as any).ngZone = this.ngZone;
  }
}
`

That is working and I'm not getting any rxjs issue either, however, I'm not able to get Angular Elements to work in BOTH an Angular consumer and Vanilla JS consumer. I've tried loading zone through a cdn but am having no luck. 

Is there anything in the works for getting Angular Elements consumed without so much configuration for any/all framework(s)?

Your input is very much appreciated!

